                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d387">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 838.51/481</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Minister <persName type="from">Blanchard</persName> to the
                            <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">American Legation</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Port au Prince</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1916-02-26T09:00:00-04:49">
                            <hi rend="italic">February 26, 1916, 9 a.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Your February 18, 4 p.m. last paragraph. Mandates are still issued by the
                    Government for payments desired by it. When received by the administrator of
                    customs the facts are inquired into and payments made, when considered proper,
                    to the individuals to whom the amounts are due, never to the Government payers.
                    While these mandates are not necessary they serve to indicate the Government’s
                    concurrence in payments made.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Blanchard</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
